The trim() method removes any leading (starting) and trailing (ending) whitespaces from the specified string.

-----
Syntax of trim():  string.trim()

-----
trim() Return Value:

returns a string with leading and trailing whitespace removed
returns the original string if there is no whitespace in the start or the end of the string

-----
Example: Java String trim()

class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    String str1 = "     Learn   Java Programming ";
    String str2 = "Learn\nJava Programming\n\n   ";
    String str3 = "     Suhas Potato        ";


    System.out.println(str1.trim());
    System.out.println(str2.trim());
    System.out.println(str3.trim());

  }
}


o/p:
Learn   Java Programming
Learn
Java Programming
Suhas Potato

//As you can see from the above example, the trim() method only removes the leading and trailing whitespace.
It doesn't remove whitespace that appears in the middle.






